  "beats": [
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "This is Liam, in for Bear. In an ideal crystal, electrons may occupy whole ranges of energy, then encounter a range where no propagating crystal state exists. That missing range is a band gap.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "provenance": "proven-core/ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "command": "Why does a repeating crystal potential create allowed energy bands separated by forbidden gaps?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — BAND THEORY",
            "segment": "Why Solids Have Forbidden Energy Gaps",
            "greeting": "Hallo, Liam",
            "runningText": "scanning the periodic spectrum…",
            "output": [
              "Real crystal momentum exists only in allowed intervals.",
              "Where the matching condition overshoots ±1, no real k solves it."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.88,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "A crystal repeats the same atomic pattern over and over. For an electron wave, that means a potential landscape with the same spacing a in every cell.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.22,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The wave must reproduce from cell to cell up to a phase. That repeating-wave requirement labels crystal states by a real wave number k.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "trace"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.68,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "In the Kronig–Penney model, solving and matching the wave gives one compact condition: cosine of k a must equal an energy-dependent function on the other side.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "transform"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.28,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "Here is the trap: cosine of any real number can never exceed plus one or fall below minus one.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.31,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Scan upward in energy. Whenever the model function lies between minus one and plus one, a real k can match it. Those energies form an allowed band.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.07,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "But whenever that function overshoots the cosine range, no real k exists. A whole energy interval disappears from the propagating spectrum: a forbidden gap.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.43,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "As the scan continues, allowed and forbidden intervals alternate. The isolated levels of one atom have broadened into bands because countless repeating cells couple together.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.28,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The gap is not a region of forbidden space. It is a range of forbidden energy for extended electron states in the ideal periodic model.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.53,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "A partially filled band lets electrons move into nearby empty states: metallic behavior. A filled band followed by a large gap resists excitation: insulating behavior.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.73,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "A semiconductor has the same band-and-gap architecture, but a modest gap. That small energy threshold is the quantum opening exploited by electronic devices.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.86,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:55:37"
      }
    },
    {
